\subsection{SPAWN OBSERVATIONS AND CALCULATIONS}\label{secSurfS}

The mean egg density for survey type $x$ in spawn $s$
(step \ref{sSpawn} in \autoref{figFlow}) is
\begin{equation}\label{eqSurfDensS}
\mean{\rho}_{xsnry} =
\frac{1}{J_{xsnry}}
\sum_{j=1}^{J_{xsnry}} \rho_{jxsnry},
\end{equation}
where $J_{xsnry}$ is the number of samples,
$\rho_{jxsnry}$ is egg density from \autoref{eqSurfDensJS}, and
$\mean{\rho}_{xsnry}$ is in $10^3 \cdot \text{eggs} \cdot \text{m}^{-2}$.
Two other metrics are required at the spawn level:
spawn length $L_{xsnry}$ and
spawn width $W_{xsnry}$, both in metres.
We set $W_{xsnry}$ to the first non-missing value of
median pool width, median Section width, median SAR width, or
observed width $W_{xsnry}'$
(in that order; \autoref{secWidthSurface}).
A pool is a group of Locations within a Section that are
often adjacent,
contain similar algae and substrate, and
can be treated as a group with likely similar widths.

The surface spawn index in spawn $s$ is
\begin{equation}\label{eqSurfIndS}
B_{xsnry}' = \frac{\mean{\rho}_{xsnry} L_{xsnry} W_{xsnry} 10^3} {\theta},
\end{equation}
where $\mean{\rho}_{xsnry}$ is mean egg density in spawn $s$ from \autoref{eqSurfDensS},
$L_{xsnry}$ is spawn length,
$W_{xsnry}$ is spawn width,
$\theta$ is the egg conversion factor from \autoref{eqECF}, and
$B_{xsnry}'$ is in tonnes (step \ref{sInd} in \autoref{figFlow}).

